          <p xml:id="Kali101-kilavi">iḵtu "āyar vēṭṭuva rāṭūut tiṇaippeya- rāvayiṉ varūuṅ kiḻavaru muḷarē" (to.po.21) eṉṉuñ cūttirattiṟ "ṟiṇainilaip peyarākiya kiḻavaruṅ kiḻattiyarum uḷar" eṉṉum vitiyāṟ koṇṭa attalaivikku avaḷ tōḻi āyar ēṟu taḻuvukiṉṟamai kāṭṭi avaḷ atu kaṇṭu varuntāmal āṇṭup peṟṟa naṉṉimittaṅ kūṟit teḷivittu, ataṉai avvitiyāṟ koṇṭa talaivaṟkuṅ kūṟi, mīṭṭum attalaivikkut tañ cuṟṟattār kūṟiyirukkuṅ kūṟṟiṉaiyuṅ kūṟit, talaivaṉum iṉṉum oruñāṉṟu ēṟutaḻuvi nammai varaintukoḷvaṉeṉṟu āṟṟuvittatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en"></p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="Kali101">
                <l>taḷipeṟu taṇpulattut talaippeyaṟ karumpīṉṟu</l> 
                <l>muḷimutaṟ potuḷiya muṭpuṟap piṭavamuṅ</l> 
                <l>kaḷipaṭṭā ṉilaiyēpōṟ ṟaṭavupu tuṭuppīṉṟu</l> 
                <l>ñelipuṭa ṉiraitta ñekiḻitaḻk kōṭalu</l>  
                <l>maṇipurai yuruviṉa kāyāvum piṟavu</l> 
                <l>maṇikoḷa malainta kaṇṇiyar tokupuṭaṉ</l> 
                <l>māṟetir koṇṭatam maintuṭa ṉiṟumār</l> 
                <l>cīṟaru muṉpiṉōṉ kaṇiccipōṟ kōṭucī</l>  
                <l>yēṟutoḻūup pukuttaṉa riyaipuṭa ṉoruṅku;</l>
                <l rend="space">avvaḻi, muḻakkeṉa viṭiyeṉa muṉcamat tārppa</l> 
                <l>vaḻakkumāṟu koṇṭu varupuvaru pīṇṭi</l> 
                <l>naṟaiyoṭu tukaḷeḻa nallava raṇiniṟpat</l> 
                <l>tuṟaiyu mālamun tolvali marāamu</l>
                <l>muṟaiyuḷi parāayp pāyntaṉar toḻūu;</l>
                <l rend="space">mēṟpāṭ ṭulaṇṭi ṉiṟaṉokkum puṉkurukka</l> 
                <l>ṇōkkañcāṉ pāynta potuvaṉaic cākkuttik</l> 
                <l>kōṭṭiṭaik koṇṭu kulaippataṉ ṟōṟṟaṅkā</l> 
                <l>ṇañcī racaiyiyal kūntaṟkai nīṭṭiyā</l> 
                <l>ṉeñcam piḷantiṭṭu nērār naṭuvaṇṭaṉ</l> 
                <l>vañciṉam vāyttāṉum pōṉm;</l>
                <l rend="space">cuṭarvirin taṉṉa curineṟṟik kāri</l>
                <l>viṭariyaṅ kaṇṇip potuvaṉaic cāṭik</l> 
                <l>kuṭarcoriyak kuttik kulaippataṉ ṟōṟṟaṅkāṇ</l> 
                <l>paṭaraṇi yantip pacuṅkaṭ kaṭavu</l> 
                <l>ḷiṭariya vēṟṟerumai neñciṭan tiṭṭuk</l>
                <l>kuṭarkūḷik kārttuvāṉ pōṉm;</l>
                <l rend="space">cevimaṟai nērmiṉṉu nuṇpoṟi veḷḷaik</l> 
                <l>kataṉañcāṉ pāynta potuvaṉaic cāṭi</l> 
                <l>nutinuṉaik kōṭṭāṟ kulaippataṉ ṟōṟṟaṅkāṇ</l>
                <l>āriru ḷeṉṉā ṉaruṅkaṅkul vantutaṉ</l> 
                <l>ṟāḷiṟ kaṭantaṭṭut tantaiyaik koṉṟāṉait</l> 
                <l>tōḷiṟ ṟirukuvāṉ pōṉm;</l>
                <l rend="space">eṉavāṅku,</l> 
                <l>aṇimālaik kēḷvaṟ ṟarūumā rāyaṉ</l> 
                <l>maṇimālai yūtuṅ kuḻal;</l>
                <l rend="space">kaṭāak kaḷiṟṟiṉuṅ kaṇṇañcā vēṟṟai</l>
                <l>viṭāatunī koḷkuvai yāyiṟ paṭāakai</l>
                <l>yīṉṟaṉa vāyamaka ṭōḷ;</l>
                <l rend="space">pakaliṭak kaṇṇiyaṉ paitaṟ kuḻalaṉ</l>
                <l>cuvaṉmicaik kōlacaitta kaiya ṉayalatu</l>
                <l>kollēṟu cāṭa viruntārkkem palliruṅ</l> 
                <l>kūnta laṇaikoṭuppēm yām;</l>
                <l rend="space">kōḷāḷa reṉṉoppā rilleṉa nammāṉuṭ</l>
                <l>ṭāḷāṇmai kūṟum potuva ṉamakkorunāṭ</l>
                <l>kēḷāḷa ṉākāmai yillai yavaṟkaṇṭu</l> 
                <l>vēḷāṇmai ceytaṉa kaṇ;</l>
                <l rend="space">āṅku, ēṟum varuntiṉa vāyarum puṇkūrntār</l> 
                <l>nāṟiruṅ kūntaṟ potumakaḷi rellāru</l>
                <l>mullaiyan taṇpoḻil pukkār potuvarō</l> 
                <l>ṭellām puṇarkuṟik koṇṭu.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>Those with chaplets worn for decoration</l>
                <l>from the thorn-backed Piṭavus thriving on dry bases,</l>
                <l>bringing forth buds to the first rain on the cool fields obtaining sprouts,</l>
                <l>from white Malabar lilies with loosening petals, crowding [and] rubbing against each other, bringing forth spatula swaying like in the condition of one drunk with toddy,</l>
                <l>from ironwood [flowers] that have a colour like sapphires and from others,</l>
                <l rend="indent8">have gathered together</l>
                <l>[and] entered, all in agreement, worshipping the bull</l>
                <l>whose horns are sharpened like the battle-axe of him with blazing rare strength,</l>
                <l corresp="1-9">in order to weigh their infatuation that receives opposition.</l>
                <l>That way, while [drums] roar before the fight like din, like thunder,</l>
                <l>coming, coming, gathering, taking the way it will roam,</l>
                <l>while incense [and] dust rise, while good [women] stand there decorated,</l>
                <l>they have spread out, revering in [their] residence</l> 
                <l corresp="10-14">the ghat, the banyan tree and the old strong Kadamba tree,</l>
                <l rend="indent8">worshipping.</l>
                <l>See the appearance of it shaking, taking between [its] horns,</l>
                <l>goring, so that he dies, a herdsman who leapt [at it], unafraid of the glances</l>
                <l>from mean brilliant eyes that resemble excessively the colour of the silkworm,</l>
                <l>similar to the one who delivered his oath</l>
                <l>among [his] foes, tearing open the heart</l>
                <l corresp="15-20">of the one who had extended a hand to the pretty, excellent, swaying tresses.</l>
                <l>See the appearance of the mountain of a black bull there,</l>
                <l>with a curly forehead expanding like fire, trample</l>
                <l>this herdsman, goring [him] so that [his] intestines spill,</l>
                <l>similar to the green-eyed god at twilight adorned with affliction,</l>
                <l>scooping up the heart of another afflicted buffalo,</l>
                <l corresp="21-26">feeding [its] intestines to [his] demons.</l>
                <l>See the appearance of the white bull with fine dots, on which</l>
                <l>ear dots flash straight, trampling the herdsman who leapt [on it],</l>
                <l>unafraid of [his] duty, [and] shaking [him] on [its] very pointed horns,</l>
                <l>similar to the one who did not heed difficult darkness,</l>
                <l>coming in difficult night, crossing with his feet, killing,</l>
                <l corresp="27-32">wrestling with [his] arms the one who killed the father.</l>
                <l>that is to say,</l>
                <l>the cowherd is blowing the flute during sapphire[-blue] evening</l>
                <l>in order to give a husband with a decorative garland.</l>
                <l>If you take without letting go</l>
                <l>the bull more fearless of eye than a rutting elephant,</l>
                <l corresp="33-38">[there are] the shoulders of the girl that have become banners.</l>
                <l>The one with a chaplet to be put by day, the one with a sad flute,</l>
                <l>the one with a hand that fastened a staff to [its] neck, in the neighbourhood,</l>
                <l>to them who remain when trampled by the murderous bull</l>
                <l corresp="39-42">we shall give a bed on our many dark tresses.</l>
                <l>The herdsman talks of effort and manliness among our cows,</l>
                <l>saying “no [bull-]taking man is equal to me.” One day</l>
                <l>there is no not-becoming [of him] as a kin man to us. Seeing him</l>
                <l corresp="43-46">[his] eyes exercise the power of desire/Vēḷ.</l>
                <l>Thus, the bulls have suffered and the cowherds abound in wounds</l>
                <l>and all the herdswomen with fragrant dark tresses</l>
                <l>have entered the cool jasmine grove</l>
                <l corresp="47-50">accepting the assignations from all the herdsmen.</l>
            </lg>
